       \begin {tikzpicture}[diagram]
         \node  (1) at (90:2.5cm) {$(kh)(gf)$};
         \node  (2) at (90+72:2.5cm) {$((kh)g)f$};
         \node  (3) at (90+2*72:2.5cm) {$(k(hg))f$};
         \node  (4) at (90+3*72:2.5cm) {$k((hg)f)$};
         \node  (5) at (90+4*72:2.5cm) {$k(h(gf))$};
         \draw  [->,morphism] (2) to node {$a_{kh,g,f}$} (1);
         \draw  [->,morphism] (1) to node {$a_{k,h,gf}$} (5);
         \draw  [->,morphism] (2) to node[swap] {$a_{k,h,g} *  \mathsf {id} _{ f } $} (3);
         \draw  [->,morphism] (3) to node[swap] {$a_{k,hg,f}$} (4);
         \draw  [->,morphism] (4) to node[swap] {$ \mathsf {id} _{ k }  * a_{h,g,f}$} (5);
       \end {tikzpicture}

Naturality of functoriality constraint: For any pair of 2-cells \alpha \colon f \to f', \beta \colon g \to g' in \mathcal { C } such that every component of the following diagram is defined, the diagram commutes.





